		  <tr>
		    <td>
		    <table align="center" border="0" width="100%" >
		    <tr>
			 <td colspan="2" height="10" width="630">
			 <a id="BulletinBoard"></a>
		     <div class="contentbox-title-green01 bg-green06 box-on">&nbsp;</div>
		     <div class="contentbox-title-green01 align-left">&nbsp;&nbsp;Network Planning</div>
		     </td>
			
			</tr>
		  </table>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr height="5"></tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p><img src=http://www.twaren.net/english/smarty/templates/images/icon_arrow_orange.gif /><font style="color: #00688B; font-weight:bold;"><strong>TWAREN is a World-Class Network</strong></font></p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p class="indent-text">The TWAREN network has been operating since Jan, 2004.  It was developed using the absolute latest network technologies and, therefore, it can offer our users a variety of new services including IPv6, Multicast, and Light Path.  Due to the need of guaranteeing service level quality to our users, TWAREN also introduced a powerful management system.  The goals of TWAREN network design are:
			</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td height="10"></td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td>
			<p class="indent-text">
			  <ul type="disc">
			    <li style="margin-bottom:6px">Hybrid technology: IP (routing) over optical Light Path (dark fiber, SDH,
      or Wavelength).</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Dual networks: production and research networks.</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Hierarchical topology: 3 tiers (cores, POPs, and end nodes).</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Multiple services.</li>
	            <li>Highly reliable, stable and flexible network.</li>
			  </ul>
			</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
	  
		  <tr>
		    <td height="10"></td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td>
			<p class="indent-text">In order to provide more efficient network operation as well as a next generation network testing platform, we are currently in the midst of network re-design to consolidate Taiwan’s two major National Research and Education Network backbones, TWAREN and TANet, with the following goals:
</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td height="10"></td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td>
			<p class="indent-text">
			  <ul type="disc">
			    <li style="margin-bottom:6px">Flexibility to different network and operation policies</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Minimum cost for network and operation re-design</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Full protection scheme for any single point of failure</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Automatic optical Light Path allocation</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Conformity to Telecommunication Management Network (TMN)
     architecture and functionalities</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Hybrid Optical Packet Infrastructure (HOPI)</li>
				<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Support for emerging network technologies</li>
				<li>Establishment of a next generation Lambda-based network testing platform</li>
			  </ul>
			</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>

 
		  <tr>
		    <td height="10"></td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p><img src=http://www.twaren.net/english/smarty/templates/images/icon_arrow_orange.gif /><font style="color: #00688B; font-weight:bold;"><strong>TWAREN Network Structure</strong></font></p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p class="indent-text">TWAREN is a hybrid network.  Its dual 20 Gbps backbone serves as the production and research networks, and its multiple optical segments are used for specific research needs such as lambda testing.
			</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p class="indent-text">TWAREN has four core nodes and 12 regional network centers (a.k.a. GigaPOPs.)   Its four core nodes are connected with a dual island-wide 20 Gbps backbone which   are provided by two fixed network carriers, <a href="http://www.cht.com.tw/" target="_blank">Chunghwa Telecom</a> and Asia Pacific Broadband Telecom.  Its 12 GigaPOPs are connected to its   backbone as 10 Gbps Metropolitan Area Networks (MANs) to bring Taiwan’s   universities and research institutions onto it.  Other networked institutions   connect to TWAREN’s backbone at their nearby GigaPOPs.  In March, 2005, Taiwan   Academic Network (TANet) started to use TWAREN’s domestic backbone to serve its   over 1,000 elementary schools, junior and senior high schools.<br />
			</p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			  <ol>
			    <li style="margin-top:15px"><strong>Core Nodes</strong></li>
				<p style="line-height:18px">TWAREN’s four core nodes are strategically placed from southern to northern Taiwan, thus, covering the entire island.  The Taipei, Hsinchu or Tainan core node is equipped with the Cisco ONS 15600, and the Taichung node is equipped with the Cisco ONS 15454 multi-service provisioning platform.  Together, the 4 core nodes form TWAREN’s primary optical switching backbone.  They are located respectively as below:</p>
			    <ul type="disc">
				    <li style="margin-bottom:6px">The Taipei Node: Taipei Technology Building</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">The Hisnchu Node: <a href="http://www.nchc.org.tw/en/" target="_blank">Hsinchu Headquarter,   NCHC</a></li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">The Tainan Node: <a href="http://noc.twaren.net/noc_eng/index.php" target="_blank">Southern Business   Unit, NCHC</a></li>
					<li>The Taichung Node: Central Business Unit, NCHC</li>
				</ul>
				
				<li style="margin-top:20px"><strong>GigaPOPs</strong></li>
				<p style="line-height:18px">TWAREN’s 12 GigaPOPs are mostly located at national universities as listing below.  They are responsible for the network management within their regions.</p>
			    <ul type="disc">
				    <li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Taiwan University (<a href="http://www.ntu.edu.tw/" target="_self">NTU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Dong Hwa University (<a href="http://www.ndhu.edu.tw" target="_self">NDHU</a>)</a></li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Central University (<a href="http://www.ncu.edu.tw/e_web/index.php" target="_self">NCU</a>)</a></li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Tsing Hua University (<a href="http://www.nthu.edu.tw" target="_self">NTHU</a>)</li>					
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Chiao Tung University (<a href="http://www.nctu.edu.tw/english/index.html" target="_self">NCTU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Chung Hsing University (<a href="http://www.nchu.edu.tw" target="_self">NCHU</a>)</li>					
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Chi Nan University (<a href="http://www.ncnu.edu.tw/web/english/index.htm" target="_self">NCNU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Chung Cheng University (<a href="http://www.ccu.edu.tw/" target="_self">CCU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Cheng Kung University (<a href="http://www.ncku.edu.tw/ver2006/en/" target="_self">NCKU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Sun Yat-sen University (<a href="http://www.nsysu.edu.tw/" target="_self">NSYSU</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">Academia Sinica (<a href="http://www.sinica.edu.tw" target="_self">SINICA</a>)</li>
					<li style="margin-bottom:6px">National Ilan University (<a href="http://www.niu.edu.tw/" target="_self">NIU</a>)</li>
				</ul>
			  
			 			
				<div class="imgborder align-center">
				  <!-- 與NOC英文網站圖同步 -->
				   <a href="http://noc.twaren.net/noc_eng/smarty/templates/images/TwarenNetworkInfra/twaren_backbone_map.jpg" title="TWAREN Backbone Map" target="_blank">
				   <img src="http://noc.twaren.net/noc_eng/smarty/templates/images/TwarenNetworkInfra/twaren_backbone_map.jpg" width="500" />
				   </a>
				   </div>
			
		  
			  <li style="margin-top:20px"><strong>Other Networked institutions</strong></li>
				<p style="line-height:18px">(including academic institutions, research centers, and local government network centers)<br /><br />
				These institutions are responsible for making their own connections to their nearby GigaPOPs.  GigaPOPs will reserve connection points for those institutions that aren't able to connect to them for now but anticipate doing so in the near future.<br /><br />				
				The detailed networked institutions are listed at: <a href="http://www.twaren.net/english/index.php?option=com_wrapper&amp;Itemid=92" target="_self">Domestic Connected Institutions</a>
				</p>
			   
			  </ol>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  
		 
		  <tr>
		    <td height="10"></td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td width="580">
			<p><img src=http://www.twaren.net/english/smarty/templates/images/icon_arrow_orange.gif /><font style="color: #00688B; font-weight:bold;"><strong>International Connectivity</strong></font></p>
			</td>
		  </tr>
		  
		  
		  <tr>
		    <td>
			<p class="indent-text">
			TWAREN has two 2.5 Gbps international trans-Pacific network connection lines. One is from Taipei to Chicago, and the other one is from Hsinchu to LA. Besides, TWAREN use a 2.5 Gbps network line to connect LA, Chicago, and New York all together. TWAREN connects to global advanced networks mainly via American advanced R&D networks: Internet2, NLR, and Pacific Wave.
      <br />
			<br />
			The detailed international peering networks are listed at: <a href="http://www.twaren.net/english/AboutTwaren/PeeringNetworks/index.php" target="_blank">International Peering</a>
			</p>
